| The most common use for stents is in [[Coronary artery|coronary arteries]], into which a [[bare-metal stent]], a [[drug-eluting stent]], or occasionally a covered stent is inserted.

[[Coronary stent]]s are placed during a [[percutaneous coronary intervention]] procedure, also known as an [[angioplasty]].
| [[Image:Taxus stent FDA.jpg|thumb|An example of a coronary stent. This version, known as a Taxus stent, has a drug-eluting function]]
|-
| [[Ureteric_stent|Ureteral stents]] are used to ensure the patency of a [[ureter]], which may be compromised, for example, by a [[kidney stone]]. This method is sometimes used as a temporary measure to prevent damage to a blocked kidney until a procedure to remove the stone can be performed. Indwelling times of 12 months or longer are indicated to hold open ureters which have been compressed by tumors in the neighbourhood of the ureter or by tumors of the ureter itself. In many cases these tumors are inoperable and the stents are used to ensure drainage of urine through the ureter. If drainage is compromised for longer periods, the kidney can be damaged. The main complications with ureteral stents are dislocation, infection, and blockage by encrustation. Recently, stents with coatings (e.g., [[heparin]]) have been approved to reduce infection, encrustation and therefore the frequency of stent replacement.
| [[File:Abdominal Xray with uretal stent.jpg|thumb|Example of a uretal stent used to alleviate [[hydronephrosis]] of the kidney]]
|-
| A urethral or [[prostatic stent]] might be needed if a man is unable to urinate. This situation often occurs when an enlarged prostate pushes against the urethra, blocking the flow of urine. The placement of a stent can open the obstruction. Recent scientific breakthroughs have confirmed the use of a prostatic stent as a viable method of dis-obstructing the prostate.  Stents can be temporary or permanent. Temporary stents can be placed in a urologist's office in a manner similar to placing a Foley catheter, requiring less than 10 minutes and using only lidocaine jelly as a local anesthetic. Clinical results<ref>{{cite journal |author=Dineen MK, Shore ND, Lumerman JH, Saslawsky MJ, Corica AP |title=Use of a temporary prostatic stent after transurethral microwave thermotherapy reduced voiding symptoms and bother without exacerbating irritative symptoms |journal=Urology |volume=71 |issue=5 |pages=873–7 |year=2008 |month=May |pmid=18374395 |doi=10.1016/j.urology.2007.12.015}}</ref> show that the temporary stent is effective and well tolerated. Permanent stents are mostly placed on an outpatient basis under local or spinal anesthesia and usually take about 30 minutes to insert. Clinical results show occurrences of migration, painful wearing, and difficult removal.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Kural AR, Tüfek I, Akpinar H, Gürtuğ A |title=Removal of urolume endoprosthesis using holmium:YAG laser |journal=J. Endourol. |volume=15 |issue=9 |pages=947–8 |year=2001 |month=November |pmid=11769852 |doi=10.1089/089277901753284198}}</ref>

Prostatic/sphincter stents can be used for draining the bladder in patients with urethra obstruction or damage to the nerves controlling the bladder.  Stents can be placed in the prostate, across the outer and inner sphincter, to achieve good drainage of the bladder. The patient requires diapers, incontinence pants/plastic pants, or an external collection device (external catheter) to collect the urine.
| [[File:Spanner insitu.jpg|thumb|Example of a stent / catheter used in the prostate to treat an enlarged prostate and provide relief in cases of obstructed urination]]
|-
| {{anchor|peripheral_artery_stent}}Stents are used in a variety of blood vessels aside from coronary arteries. Stents may be used as a component of [[Angioplasty#Peripheral angioplasty|peripheral artery angioplasty]].
| [[File:Stent4 fcm.jpg|thumb|Stents for peripheral vessels]]
